"""
MKT Context — Exodus chapters 33–35
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-exodus-33-35.py

Chapter coverage:
  ch33 = 23 verses — Moses's intercession for divine presence; the tent outside
         the camp; the theophany request; the cleft of the rock
  ch34 = 35 verses — second tablets; the Sinai theophany and 13 attributes;
         covenant renewal (ritual/cultic Decalogue); Moses's radiant face
  ch35 = 35 verses — Sabbath restated; freewill offering call; people respond;
         Bezalel and Oholiab re-commissioned

Key decisions:
- The 13 divine attributes (34:6-7) receive full treatment as the canonical
  centre of OT theology of God's character; quotation network noted
- karan (radiant face, 34:29-35) vs. qeren (horn): etymology and mistranslation
  history noted; Vulgate cornuta -> Michelangelo noted but not dwelt on
- Ch 35 Sabbath passage deliberately shorter since ch 31:12-17 already covered
  the same legislation in detail; context focuses on new element (its placement
  before tabernacle-building shows priority over sacred construction)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EXODUS_CONTEXT = {
  "33": {
    "1": "<p><b>'Depart; go up from here, you and the people whom you have brought up out of the land of Egypt, to the land of which I swore to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob':</b> The command resumes the original Abrahamic itinerary after the golden-calf crisis. YHWH still fulfills the land-promise, but the relationship has been fractured. The distancing is lexical: God had said 'I will bring you' (6:8); now it is 'go up.' The territorial promise stands; the personal accompanying presence is the contested question through the rest of the chapter.</p>",
    "2": "<p><b>'I will send an angel before you, and I will drive out the Canaanites, the Amorites, the Hittites, the Perizzites, the Hivites, and the Jebusites':</b> The angel substitute is the same offered in 23:20-23 (before the golden calf) but now proposed as a replacement for God's direct presence rather than as an advance agent alongside it. The six-nation list is the standard formula for Canaan's inhabitants (Deut 7:1); their expulsion remains promised, but it will be accomplished through the mediation of an angel rather than the immediate theophanic presence that guided the plagues.</p>",
    "3": "<p><b>'Go up to a land flowing with milk and honey; but I will not go up among you, lest I consume you on the way, for you are a stiff-necked people':</b> The self-restraint God announces is motivated by the fear of destroying Israel — God's holiness is so consuming that an unmediated presence among a rebellious people would be fatal. The phrase <em>qesheh-oref</em> (stiff-necked) appears again from 32:9; the golden-calf characterization becomes the permanent theological explanation for the angel-substitution. The same tension — how can a holy God dwell among sinful people? — drives the entire tabernacle theology of Leviticus.</p>",
    "4": "<p><b>When the people heard this disastrous word, they mourned, and no one put on his ornaments:</b> The national mourning response — taking off jewelry — is the physical enactment of the spiritual reality: the gold that had been used for the golden calf must not be worn. The Hebrew <em>ra</em> (bad/evil/disastrous) applied to YHWH's word is striking; it acknowledges that the divine decree genuinely grieves Israel, and the grief is appropriate. The removal of ornaments mirrors the later practice of wearing sackcloth in mourning; external symbols of status are abandoned when the relationship with God is damaged.</p>",
    "5": "<p><b>YHWH said to Moses, 'Say to the people of Israel, You are a stiff-necked people; if for a single moment I should go up among you, I would consume you. So now take off your ornaments, that I may know what to do with you':</b> The divine indecision expressed here — 'that I may know what to do with you' (<em>ve'eda mah e'eseh lakh</em>) — is one of the most remarkable anthropomorphic expressions in the Torah. The sovereign God pauses, as if calibrating his response to Israel's moral state, leaving the outcome genuinely open. This openness is the space that Moses's intercession fills in vv12-17.</p>",
    "6": "<p><b>Therefore the people of Israel stripped themselves of their ornaments, from Mount Horeb onward:</b> The permanent removal of ornaments from Horeb onward may have been the origin of a later Israelite mourning custom; the rabbis connected it to the wearing of <em>tefillin</em> as an alternative to jewelry — the sign of covenant devotion replacing personal adornment. The phrase 'from Mount Horeb' fixes the beginning of the practice at the precise location of the covenant, the place where the ornamental gold was first corrupted into the calf.</p>",
    "7": "<p><b>Now Moses used to take the tent and pitch it outside the camp, far off from the camp, and he called it the tent of meeting. And everyone who sought YHWH would go out to the tent of meeting, which was outside the camp:</b> This 'tent of meeting' is not the Tabernacle (not yet built) but a temporary proto-sanctuary established by Moses in response to the broken relationship. Its placement <em>outside the camp</em> and <em>far off</em> (<em>harchek</em>) spatially embodies the fractured presence: YHWH is accessible but distanced. The Tabernacle, when built, will be positioned at the <em>center</em> of the camp (Num 2); the contrast between this temporary outside-tent and the eventual central Tabernacle is the narrative arc of the restoration.</p>",
    "8": "<p><b>Whenever Moses went out to the tent, all the people would rise up, and each would stand at his tent door, and watch Moses until he had gone into the tent:</b> The communal attention to Moses's approach to the tent — every person standing at their own tent door — depicts Israel's collective longing for restored access to God through Moses's mediation. The spatial drama of the scene (Moses walking from the camp center toward the far-off tent while all of Israel watches) functions as public theology: the people know that what happens in that tent between Moses and God determines their fate.</p>",
    "9": "<p><b>When Moses entered the tent, the pillar of cloud would descend and stand at the entrance of the tent, and YHWH would speak with Moses:</b> The cloud-pillar's descent to the tent-entrance (not inside, not overhead, but at the door) reflects the same threshold-presence theology as the Passover blood at the doorposts. YHWH meets Moses at the boundary of the sacred space, and the whole camp sees the cloud descend — a public theophanic sign that the mediator has entered into divine council.</p>",
    "10": "<p><b>And when all the people saw the pillar of cloud standing at the entrance of the tent, all the people would rise up and worship, each at his tent door:</b> The communal response of worship — each person at their own tent door, watching the cloud at Moses's tent — is a distributed liturgy: no priest, no altar, no sacrifice, but the entire camp oriented toward the visible presence of God through an act of simultaneous prostration. This is one of the only scenes in the Pentateuch where all Israel worships simultaneously without any formal cultic mechanism.</p>",
    "11": "<p><b>Thus YHWH used to speak to Moses face to face, as a man speaks to his friend:</b> The phrase <em>panim el panim</em> (face to face) creates a deliberate tension with v20 (you cannot see my face and live) that the narrative never fully resolves. The Num 12:6-8 parallel elaborates: Moses receives direct speech, not visions or dreams like other prophets; Deut 34:10 uses the same formula as Moses's epitaph. The 'friend' (<em>rea</em>) register is the most intimate human relationship vocabulary; its application to Moses's divine encounter makes him categorically different from all subsequent prophets. The NT applies this intimacy to Jesus (John 15:15: 'no longer servants but friends').</p>",
    "12": "<p><b>Moses said to YHWH, 'See, you say to me: Bring up this people — but you have not let me know whom you will send with me. Yet you have said: I know you by name, and you have also found favor in my sight':</b> Moses's intercession strategy is to hold YHWH accountable to his own prior declarations. The argument is formally legal: if YHWH has said he knows Moses by name and Moses has found favor, then YHWH's promise of accompaniment must follow. The phrase <em>yada'ticha beshem</em> (I know you by name) is the language of personal, covenantal election (Isa 45:3-4; John 10:3) — Moses argues from divine election to divine obligation.</p>",
    "13": "<p><b>'Now therefore, if I have found favor in your sight, please show me your ways, that I may know you in order to find favor in your sight. Consider too that this nation is your people':</b> Moses's request escalates from the practical (who goes with us) to the theological (show me your ways). <em>Hora'eni na et darkekha</em> (show me please your ways) — the plural <em>darkekha</em> (your ways) asks for the comprehensive pattern of divine action, not merely an itinerary. The final argument — 'this nation is your people' (<em>amcha ha-goi hazeh</em>) — is the same move as in 32:11-13: God's name is bound up with Israel's fate; what happens to them reflects on him.</p>",
    "14": "<p><b>And he said, 'My presence (<em>panim</em>) will go with you, and I will give you rest':</b> The divine response grants Moses's petition. <em>Panai yeleku</em> (my face/presence will go) — <em>panim</em> (face/presence) is the Hebrew word for both the face and the person; YHWH commits to go as the one who is present, not to send a representative. The promise of <em>menuchah</em> (rest) anticipates the rest given in the land (Deut 12:9-10; 1 Kgs 8:56; Ps 95:11) — the ultimate goal of the exodus trajectory. The writer of Hebrews interprets this rest eschatologically (Heb 3:7-4:13).</p>",
    "15": "<p><b>And he said to him, 'If your presence (<em>panim</em>) will not go with me, do not bring us up from here':</b> Moses refuses to accept anything less than the full divine presence. The conditional is absolute: not the land, not the angel, not the promise — without <em>panim</em>, no advance. This is one of the most theologically concentrated statements about the nature of worship in the entire Pentateuch: the goal of the exodus is not land but God. The land without God's presence is worthless; God's presence makes any location adequate. The principle grounds later exile theology: the presence of God can be with Israel in Babylon.</p>",
    "16": "<p><b>'For how shall it be known that I have found favor in your sight, I and your people? Is it not in your going with us, so that we are distinct (<em>nifleinu</em>) from every other people on the face of the earth?':</b> The verb <em>nifleinu</em> (we are set apart/distinguished/made distinct) uses the same root as <em>pala</em> (to do wonders, to distinguish). God's presence is the sole distinguishing mark of Israel from all nations — not ethnic identity, not territorial possession, not military might. The theological vision is eschatological: all nations that do not have the divine <em>panim</em> are fundamentally the same. Israel's uniqueness is entirely relational, not intrinsic.</p>",
    "17": "<p><b>And YHWH said to Moses, 'This very thing that you have spoken I will do, for you have found favor in my sight, and I know you by name':</b> The divine grant uses the same formula as Moses's argument (v12) — a reciprocal echo confirming that Moses's reasoning was legally valid. The petition succeeded not because of Israel's merit but because of Moses's covenantal standing with God. Intercessory prayer in the OT works through the mediator's relationship with God, not the petitioner's own righteousness — the same theology that grounds NT intercession through Christ (Heb 7:25).</p>",
    "18": "<p><b>Moses said, 'Please show me your glory (<em>kabodekha</em>)':</b> Moses escalates from asking for <em>panim</em> (presence, v14-15) and <em>darkekha</em> (ways, v13) to asking for <em>kavod</em> (glory, H3519). The <em>kavod</em> vocabulary is weightier even than <em>panim</em>: it is the substantial, weighty, manifest effulgence of divine being — what Isaiah sees in the throne-room (Isa 6:3), what the Tabernacle is filled with (40:34-35), what Ezekiel sees departing Jerusalem (Ezek 10:18-19). The request follows naturally from Moses's deepening intimacy with YHWH: having secured the presence, he now asks to see it fully.</p>",
    "19": "<p><b>And he said, 'I will make all my goodness (<em>tuvi</em>) pass before you and will proclaim before you my name YHWH. And I will be gracious to whom I will be gracious, and will show mercy on whom I will show mercy':</b> YHWH substitutes <em>tov</em> (goodness/beauty) for <em>kavod</em> (glory) — a distinction between the full divine reality and the experienced passage of divine character. The self-predication formula <em>ve-chanoti et asher achon ve-richamti et asher arachem</em> (I will be gracious to whom I will be gracious, and will show mercy on whom I will show mercy) is cited by Paul in Rom 9:15 as the definitive text for divine sovereignty in election. The doubling (gracious... gracious; merciful... merciful) creates an absolute sovereignty claim: God's grace is not obligated by any prior consideration except God's own will.</p>",
    "20": "<p><b>'But,' he said, 'you cannot see my face, for man shall not see me and live':</b> The prohibition on seeing the divine face (<em>lo tuchal lirot et panai ki lo-yirani ha-adam vachai</em>) is the absolute limit on theophanic encounter in the Mosaic covenant. The reasoning is not arbitrary but physical-metaphysical: the full manifestation of divine holiness is incompatible with mortal existence. Earlier theophanies (Jacob 'seeing God face to face' at Peniel, Gen 32:30; Moses and the elders 'seeing God' at the covenant meal, Exod 24:10-11) are retrospectively protected events where God chose to limit his self-disclosure; the rule remains.</p>",
    "21": "<p><b>And YHWH said, 'Behold, there is a place by me where you shall stand on the rock':</b> The geography of theophany: <em>makom</em> (place) is the neutral word for sacred space in Genesis-Deuteronomy (Gen 28:11 at Bethel; Deut 12:5 for the central sanctuary). Standing <em>alai</em> (by me, near me) on the rock while God passes is the maximum proximity that mortal flesh can sustain. The rock (<em>tsur</em>, H6697) at Horeb/Sinai is the same rock from which water flowed (17:6); Paul identifies the rock as Christ (1 Cor 10:4), and the cleft of the rock receives both Christ as the source of life and the one hidden within him.</p>",
    "22": "<p><b>'And while my glory passes by I will put you in a cleft of the rock, and I will cover you with my hand until I have passed by':</b> The cleft of the rock (<em>niqrat ha-tsur</em>) is a natural recess in the cliff face; Moses is placed inside it and shielded by the divine hand during the passage of glory. The word <em>niqrat</em> (cleft/hollow/opening) appears only here in the OT; its singularity underscores the uniqueness of the event. The image of God's hand covering the prophet during theophany resonates with Elijah at Horeb (1 Kgs 19:9-13, hiding in a cave while YHWH passes), which is likely the most direct literary parallel.</p>",
    "23": "<p><b>'Then I will take away my hand, and you shall see my back (<em>achorai</em>), but my face shall not be seen':</b> <em>Achorai</em> (H268, my back/after-parts/receding form) — not the literal back of an anthropomorphic figure but the diminished, indirect perception of God after the full divine presence has passed. The Jewish commentator Rashi interpreted this as Moses seeing the knot of God's tefillin (a playful but theologically serious image: the divine afterglow is God's covenant-sign). The more theological reading: <em>achorai</em> is the experienceable residue of divine passage — the sense of having been in the presence of God — which is all mortal existence can contain.</p>"
  },
  "34": {
    "1": "<p><b>'Cut for yourself two tablets of stone like the first, and I will write on the tablets the words that were on the first tablets, which you broke':</b> The second tablets differ from the first in one detail: Moses cuts them, God writes on them (v28 confirms God wrote the words). The first tablets were entirely God's work (31:18); the second require Moses's labor. The covenant renewal is genuine but not identical to the original — Israel's sin has changed the terms of the relationship. The phrase 'which you broke' (<em>asher shibarta</em>) is noted without condemnation; the breaking was a covenantally necessary act, not a sin.</p>",
    "2": "<p><b>'Be ready in the morning, and come up in the morning to Mount Sinai, and present yourself there to me on the top of the mountain':</b> The morning timing of theophany is consistent with the earlier Sinai events (19:16, 24:4) and with the liturgical pattern of dawn as the prime time of divine encounter (Ps 30:5, 'weeping may tarry for the night, but joy comes with the morning'). The mountain ascent without the people mirrors Moses's first ascent; the renewal is bilateral between YHWH and Moses, not a communal event.</p>",
    "3": "<p><b>'No one shall come up with you, and let no one be seen throughout all the mountain. Let no flocks or herds graze opposite that mountain':</b> The exclusion of all other persons and even animals replicates the conditions of the original Sinai theophany (19:12-13, 24) but strips it down to the minimum: Moses alone. The prohibition on animals grazing near the mountain reflects the contagious holiness of the theophanic site — sacred space radiates outward and cannot be casually entered. The fence-around-the-mountain principle is intensified by the golden calf catastrophe: there are no deputies this time.</p>",
    "4": "<p><b>So Moses cut two tablets of stone like the first. And he rose early in the morning and went up on Mount Sinai, as YHWH had commanded him, and took in his hand two tablets of stone:</b> The compliance formula confirms Moses's obedience precisely to the instructions of vv1-3: the same tablets, the same timing, the same ascent. The spare narrative — Moses carrying the tablets up the mountain — sets the scene for one of the most theologically concentrated texts in the entire Pentateuch.</p>",
    "5": "<p><b>YHWH descended in the cloud and stood with him there, and proclaimed the name of YHWH:</b> The cloud descent — the pillar of cloud as the vehicle of theophany — is the same medium as at the tent of meeting (33:9) and the Tabernacle (40:34-35). The verb <em>vayiqra beshem YHWH</em> (and he proclaimed in the name of YHWH) can be read as either YHWH proclaiming his own name or Moses proclaiming YHWH's name; the parallelism with v6 (where the subject is clearly YHWH) and the Jewish liturgical tradition both favor YHWH self-proclaiming. The name-proclamation in vv6-7 is the substance of what was promised in 33:19 (I will proclaim my name YHWH before you).</p>",
    "6": "<p><b>YHWH passed before him and proclaimed, 'YHWH, YHWH, a God merciful (<em>rachum</em>) and gracious (<em>chanun</em>), slow to anger (<em>erekh apayim</em>), and abounding in steadfast love (<em>chesed</em>) and faithfulness (<em>emet</em>)':</b> The opening four attributes of what Jewish tradition calls the <em>Shelosh Esreh Middot</em> (13 divine attributes, vv6-7) constitute the most important systematic statement of God's character in the Hebrew Bible. The double repetition of <em>YHWH, YHWH</em> has been variously interpreted: God's name proclaimed twice for emphasis; the God of the past (before the sin) and present (after the sin) who remains the same; or the two covenantal moments (the original giving and the renewal). <em>Rachum</em> (compassionate, from <em>rechem</em>, womb — the deep maternal compassion of a mother for her child) and <em>chanun</em> (gracious, disposition of undeserved favor) are the foundational pair. <em>Erekh apayim</em> (literally long of nostrils — the idiom for patient restraint of anger) uses the physical image of controlled breathing. <em>Chesed</em> (steadfast love/loyal covenant love) and <em>emet</em> (faithfulness/truth) are the paired covenant-relationship virtues.</p>",
    "7": "<p><b>'Keeping steadfast love for thousands, forgiving iniquity and transgression and sin, but who will by no means clear the guilty, visiting the iniquity of the fathers on the children and the children's children, to the third and the fourth generation':</b> The 13th attribute (by traditional counting) and the limit: YHWH will by no means clear (<em>venaqqeh lo yenaqqeh</em>, an absolute negative formed with the infinitive absolute) the guilty. The juxtaposition of unlimited forgiveness (for thousands) and unavoidable accountability (to the fourth generation) captures the essential tension in biblical theology of judgment and mercy. The <em>paqad avon avot</em> (visiting the iniquity of the fathers) is not inherited guilt but the social consequence of sin that spreads through communities and generations; the Decalogue version (20:5) identifies it specifically with idol-worship. Ezekiel 18 later argues against any mechanical generational guilt, clarifying that each individual is accountable for their own sin.</p>",
    "8": "<p><b>And Moses quickly bowed his head toward the earth and worshiped:</b> <em>Vayimmaher Mosheh vayiqod artza vayishtachu</em> (Moses hurried and bowed to the earth and worshiped) — the immediacy of the prostration (<em>maher</em>, quickly) signals the overwhelming impact of the theophany. The man who spoke to God 'face to face as a friend' (33:11) collapses into immediate adoration at the proclamation of the divine character. The worship gesture is earth-directed: the full body pressed to the ground, the face down — the maximal acknowledgment of the chasm between divine and human.</p>",
    "9": "<p><b>And he said, 'If now I have found favor in your sight, O Lord, please let the Lord go in the midst of us, for it is a stiff-necked people, and pardon our iniquity and our sin, and take us for your inheritance':</b> Moses's petition immediately follows the divine character proclamation — he uses the attributes just declared as the ground for his request. <em>Sacha avoneinu vechatateinu</em> (pardon our iniquity and our sin) — the prayer for forgiveness cites the two terms just used in v7 as forgiven by God. The request to be God's <em>nachalah</em> (inheritance/portion) reverses the relational movement: not Israel claiming God as their inheritance but Israel asking to be claimed as God's possession. Deut 9:26,29 uses the same <em>nachalah</em> vocabulary in Moses's retelling of this prayer.</p>",
    "10": "<p><b>And he said, 'Behold, I am making a covenant. Before all your people I will do marvels such as have not been created in all the earth or in any nation':</b> The covenant renewal is explicitly called a new making (<em>karet berit</em>, cutting a covenant) — the same language as the original covenant of Exod 24. The promise of unprecedented marvels (<em>niflaot</em>) anticipates the conquest; the phrase 'never been created in all the earth or among any nation' uses creation language (<em>nibra'u</em>, from <em>bara</em>, the same verb as Gen 1:1) for historical events, indicating that YHWH's acts in history are as categorically unique as the original creation.</p>",
    "11": "<p><b>'Observe what I command you this day. Behold, I will drive out before you the Amorites, the Canaanites, the Hittites, the Perizzites, the Hivites, and the Jebusites':</b> The covenant renewal re-states the territorial promise from 33:2. The six-nation expulsion list is the standard Deuteronomic formulation; its repetition here is deliberate — the covenant renewal does not subtract from the territorial promise despite the golden-calf rupture. YHWH's fidelity to the Abrahamic land-promise is unconditional; the Mosaic covenant's conditions govern how Israel inhabits the land, not whether they receive it.</p>",
    "12": "<p><b>'Take care, lest you make a covenant with the inhabitants of the land to which you go, lest it become a snare in your midst':</b> The prohibition on treaty-making with Canaan's inhabitants is the political application of exclusive covenant loyalty. <em>Moqesh</em> (snare/trap) — the same word used by Pharaoh's officials for Moses himself (10:7). Covenants in the ANE created formal social bonds, including obligations of mutual aid and, often, cultural exchange including religious syncretism. The prohibition is not xenophobic but theological: the integrity of Israel's covenant with YHWH cannot coexist with formal treaty bonds to societies organized around rival deities.</p>",
    "13": "<p><b>'You shall tear down their altars and break their pillars and cut down their Asherim':</b> The three objects listed — <em>mizbeach</em> (altar), <em>matsevah</em> (standing stone/pillar), and <em>asherah</em> (carved wooden pole representing the Canaanite goddess Asherah) — are the three essential components of a Canaanite high-place. The destruction mandate is comprehensive: no coexistence with the physical infrastructure of alien worship. The archaeological record of Iron Age I Canaan shows exactly these types of cultic installations at numerous sites; the Deuteronomistic History's recurring critique is that Israel failed to destroy them (1 Kgs 14:23; 2 Kgs 23:14).</p>",
    "14": "<p><b>'You shall worship no other god, for YHWH, whose name is Jealous (<em>qanna</em>), is a jealous God':</b> The divine name <em>Qanna</em> (Jealous, H7067) appears only here and in Deut 4:24 and 6:15. <em>Qin'ah</em> (jealousy/zeal, H7065) in the divine context is not pettiness but the passionate, exclusive covenantal claim of a personal relationship: YHWH's jealousy is analogous to a husband's jealousy for exclusive relational fidelity, not arbitrary possessiveness. The OT's marriage metaphor for the covenant (Hosea, Jeremiah, Ezekiel) is anticipated in this vocabulary.</p>",
    "15": "<p><b>'Lest you make a covenant with the inhabitants of the land, and when they whore after their gods and sacrifice to their gods and you are invited, you eat of his sacrifice':</b> The path of apostasy runs through the social invitation to share in pagan sacrificial meals. The phrase <em>wiznu acharei eloheihem</em> (whore after their gods) introduces the sexual/covenant-infidelity metaphor that will dominate Hosea, Jeremiah, and Ezekiel. Participation in a sacrificial meal in the ancient world created a binding social and religious relationship — the same concern Paul addresses in 1 Corinthians 8-10 regarding food offered to idols in the Greco-Roman context.</p>",
    "16": "<p><b>'And you take of their daughters for your sons, and their daughters whore after their gods and make your sons whore after their gods':</b> The intermarriage prohibition is framed generationally: the first generation marries across the covenant boundary; the next generation inherits the religious syncretism. The social-transmission model of apostasy (through marriage, then children's formation) is precisely what the book of Judges dramatizes as the pattern of each generation's decline. Solomon's foreign wives and their altars (1 Kgs 11:1-8) are the definitive royal case study of this exact pattern.</p>",
    "17": "<p><b>'You shall not make for yourself any gods of cast metal (<em>elohei massekhah</em>)':</b> The prohibition immediately after the social-contamination warning is no accident: the golden calf was an <em>egel massekhah</em> (cast metal calf, 32:4). The covenant renewal's specific re-statement of this prohibition in the context of intermarriage and syncretism completes the literary arc from the calf-making to the covenant-renewal: the law that was violated is the law that is reinscribed.</p>",
    "18": "<p><b>'You shall keep the Feast of Unleavened Bread. Seven days you shall eat unleavened bread, as I commanded you, at the time appointed in the month Abib, for in the month Abib you came out from Egypt':</b> The three pilgrimage feasts (Unleavened Bread/Passover, Weeks/Harvest, Booths/Ingathering) anchor the covenant renewal's ritual obligations. The repetition here from 23:14-17 in the so-called 'Book of the Covenant' suggests this is the ritual core of the renewed covenant, not merely a repetition. The agricultural calendar — Abib (spring barley), Weeks (summer wheat), Ingathering (autumn) — ties Israel's worship to the land's own rhythm, embedding covenant fidelity in the cycle of creation.</p>",
    "19": "<p><b>'All that open the womb are mine, all your male livestock, the firstborn of cow and sheep':</b> The firstborn dedication law restate from 13:2,12-15; its placement in the covenant renewal ties it directly to the Passover redemption — the firstborn of Israel was spared by YHWH's action; therefore the firstborn of every animal belongs to YHWH as acknowledgment of that redemption. The ritual economics of the tabernacle/temple system are grounded in this foundational ownership claim.</p>",
    "20": "<p><b>'The firstborn of a donkey you shall redeem with a lamb, or if you will not redeem it you shall break its neck. All the firstborn of your sons you shall redeem. And none shall appear before me empty-handed':</b> The donkey is the only clean-category animal that cannot be offered directly (being a work animal, not a sacrificial animal); it requires a substitute (lamb) or destruction. The firstborn son requires redemption — anticipating the later <em>pidyon haben</em> ceremony — grounding the obligation in the exodus rescue. <em>Velo yera'u fanai reqam</em> (none shall appear before me empty-handed) — the pilgrimage feast obligation to bring an offering is a covenantal requirement, not a voluntary gesture.</p>",
    "21": "<p><b>'Six days you shall work, but on the seventh day you shall rest. In plowing time and in harvest you shall rest':</b> The Sabbath re-statement within the covenant renewal adds a crucial agricultural precision: even during plowing and harvest — the two most time-critical agricultural periods — the Sabbath stands. The economic pressure of plowing season (seed must go in at the right moment) and harvest (grain must be cut before it falls) is the maximum test of Sabbath obedience. The covenant renewal specifically closes this exemption loophole.</p>",
    "22": "<p><b>'You shall observe the Feast of Weeks (<em>chag shavuot</em>), the firstfruits of wheat harvest, and the Feast of Ingathering at the year's end':</b> <em>Shavuot</em> (Weeks, H7620) — counted seven weeks from the Feast of Unleavened Bread; in Second Temple tradition it became associated with the giving of the Torah at Sinai, making it the annual commemoration of the covenant renewal event described in this very chapter. The Christian feast of Pentecost — fifty days after Passover — falls on the same calendar day and receives the outpouring of the Spirit, which is interpreted in Acts 2 as a new-covenant fulfillment of the Sinai gift of the law (Jer 31:33).</p>",
    "23": "<p><b>'Three times in the year shall all your males appear before YHWH God, the God of Israel':</b> The three annual pilgrimage feasts create the structure of Israel's sacred year. <em>Kol-zekhurcha</em> (all your males) — the adult male population is obligated to appear; women, children, and slaves could attend but were not legally required. The centralization of these feasts at the later Temple (Deut 16:16) would make Jerusalem the pivot of Israelite national and religious identity for every Passover, Shavuot, and Sukkot generation.</p>",
    "24": "<p><b>'For I will cast out nations before you and enlarge your borders; no one shall covet your land, when you go up to appear before YHWH your God three times in the year':</b> The protection of Israel's land during the pilgrimage feasts — when the male population leaves their borders undefended — is an explicit divine promise. YHWH covenants to restrain the nations' appetite for Israel's territory during the three periods when Israel is most militarily vulnerable. The faith-structure is visible: going up to worship requires trusting God with the national security that worship's absence would seem to ensure.</p>",
    "25": "<p><b>'You shall not offer the blood of my sacrifice with leaven, and the sacrifice of the Feast of the Passover shall not be left until the morning':</b> The Passover regulations restated from 12:10,15 — no leaven with the blood, no overnight storage. The repetition in the covenant renewal context reinforces that these requirements are covenantally binding, not merely ceremonial best practices.</p>",
    "26": "<p><b>'The best of the firstfruits of your ground you shall bring to the house of YHWH your God. You shall not boil a young goat in its mother's milk':</b> The two regulations juxtaposed here — firstfruits offering and the milk-boiling prohibition — are the canonical pair. The firstfruits obligation (reshit bikkurei adamatekha) grounds Israel's agricultural relationship to the land in covenant gratitude. The prohibition on boiling a kid in its mother's milk appears three times (23:19; 34:26; Deut 14:21) and became the founding text for the Jewish dietary separation of meat and dairy. Its original meaning is disputed: it may prohibit a specific Canaanite ritual (no direct evidence), or it may express a general ethic of not using a mother's life-giving substance to kill her offspring.</p>",
    "27": "<p><b>And YHWH said to Moses, 'Write these words, for in accordance with these words I have made a covenant with you and with Israel':</b> The written character of the covenant is essential: it is not merely oral tradition but an inscribed, durable document. Moses writes the covenant terms; God writes the Ten Commandments on the tablets (v28). The dual-authorship structure of the written covenant — human scribe and divine inscriber — parallels the nature of the entire Torah as both humanly composed and divinely authorized.</p>",
    "28": "<p><b>So he was there with YHWH forty days and forty nights. He neither ate bread nor drank water. And he wrote on the tablets the words of the covenant, the Ten Commandments (<em>aseret hadevarim</em>):</b> The second forty-day fast without food or water is, like the first (24:18), a miraculous suspension of normal human limitation for the purpose of covenant mediation. <em>Aseret ha-devarim</em> (the Ten Words/Commandments) — the only place in Exodus where the Decalogue receives this summary name; Deuteronomy uses it as well (4:13; 10:4). The phrase identifies the tablets' content as the foundational covenant text, distinct from the fuller legal corpus of Exodus 21-23 and Leviticus.</p>",
    "29": "<p><b>When Moses came down from Mount Sinai, with the two tablets of the testimony in his hand as he came down from the mountain, Moses did not know that the skin of his face shone (<em>karan or panav</em>) because he had been talking with God:</b> <em>Karan</em> (H7160, to shoot out rays, to shine/radiate) is the Qal perfect of the verb derived from <em>qeren</em> (horn/ray). The homophony between shining and horning led Jerome in the Latin Vulgate (4th c. AD) to translate <em>cornuta esset facies sua</em> (his face was horned), which became the iconographic source for the famous horned Moses of Michelangelo's sculpture and medieval art generally. The correct meaning — radiance of light — is confirmed by the parallel in 2 Cor 3:7-18 where Paul uses the Greek <em>doxa</em> (glory) for Moses's shining face.</p>",
    "30": "<p><b>And when Aaron and all the people of Israel saw Moses, behold, the skin of his face shone, and they were afraid to come near him:</b> The communal response of fear to Moses's radiance is theologically significant: the man who mediates YHWH's glory becomes himself a secondary source of holy terror. The same vocabulary of dread (<em>yare'u</em>) used for encountering YHWH in theophany (3:6; 19:16-20) now applies to Moses's transformed face. Moses has become, through covenantal intimacy with God, a dangerous object requiring the same respectful distance as the divine presence itself.</p>",
    "31": "<p><b>But Moses called to them, and Aaron and all the leaders of the congregation returned to him, and Moses talked with them:</b> Moses must actively call the people back; their fear is genuine. The leaders (<em>nesi'ei ha-edah</em>) return first — the appropriate hierarchy, moving from communal leadership to the broader assembly in v32. The pattern mirrors the Sinai theophany itself, where the people stood at a distance while Moses approached the thick darkness (20:18-21).</p>",
    "32": "<p><b>And afterward all the people of Israel came near, and he commanded them all that YHWH had spoken with him on Mount Sinai:</b> The full assembly receives Moses's instruction after the leaders. The covenant renewal is publicly communicated; it is not a private transaction between Moses and YHWH but the renewed basis of national life transmitted through the mediator to the entire community.</p>",
    "33": "<p><b>And when Moses had finished speaking with them, he put a veil (<em>masveh</em>) over his face:</b> <em>Masveh</em> (H4533, veil/covering) — the veil is applied <em>after</em> speaking with the people, not during. Moses's face shines during divine encounter and human transmission; the veil covers the residual radiance when he is not actively conveying divine word. The social function of the veil is not to hide but to demarcate: the shining face is for covenant communication; ordinary time is veiled. Paul's interpretation in 2 Cor 3:13-18 is that Moses veiled his face to prevent Israel from seeing the 'end of what was passing away' — the fading glory — and uses this to argue that the new covenant's glory is permanent and unveiled.</p>",
    "34": "<p><b>Whenever Moses went in before YHWH to speak with him, he would remove the veil, until he came out. And when he came out and told the people of Israel what he was commanded':</b> The veil-removal pattern: Moses removes the veil to enter YHWH's presence, receives instruction, exits, communicates it with the shining face exposed, then re-veils when the transmission is done. The rhythm maps the transmission cycle of revelation: divine source → mediator → community, with the shining face marking active transmission moments.</p>",
    "35": "<p><b>The people of Israel would see the face of Moses, that the skin of Moses's face was shining. And Moses would put the veil over his face again, until he went in to speak with him:</b> The closing verse of the chapter creates the framework for interpreting all subsequent Mosaic teaching in Exodus and Leviticus: Moses's authority as teacher derives from his radiant, theophany-bearing face, which is the sign of his direct access to YHWH. The veil-cycle is the visual grammar of prophetic mediation in Israel's experience. Paul (2 Cor 3:18) contrasts this with believers in Christ who 'with unveiled face behold the glory of the Lord and are being transformed into the same image from one degree of glory to another.'</p>"
  },
  "35": {
    "1": "<p><b>Moses assembled all the congregation of Israel and said to them, 'These are the things that YHWH has commanded you to do':</b> The transitional verse opening the Tabernacle construction section (chs 35-40) begins with Moses assembling <em>kol adat benei Yisrael</em> — the whole congregation, all of Israel. This is the same assembly formula used for major covenant occasions (12:3, 16:1, 17:1). What follows is not merely construction instructions but the communal execution of a national covenant obligation. The Tabernacle is Israel's covenant project; it belongs to all of them.</p>",
    "2": "<p><b>'Six days work shall be done, but on the seventh day you shall have a Sabbath of solemn rest, holy to YHWH. Whoever does any work on it shall be put to death':</b> The Sabbath is the first thing Moses communicates after assembling the entire congregation — it is placed before the Tabernacle building instructions for deliberate theological emphasis. Even the sacred construction project cannot override the Sabbath. The phrase <em>Shabbat Shabbaton</em> (Sabbath of solemn rest) places this Sabbath statement in the same intensified register as the Day of Atonement (Lev 16:31) and the Jubilee year (Lev 25:4). The death penalty for violation confirms that the Sabbath is covenantally constitutive.</p>",
    "3": "<p><b>'You shall kindle no fire in all your dwelling places on the Sabbath day':</b> The fire prohibition is the single specific Sabbath restriction added to this re-statement that was not in the 31:12-17 version. Its practical implication would include cooking, metalwork, and lighting — the most common daily activities involving fire. The Rabbinic tradition built the entire 39-category system of forbidden Sabbath work (m. Shabbat 7:2) from the juxtaposition of the Sabbath command here with the Tabernacle construction instructions that follow — the 39 categories are derived from the types of labor used to build the Tabernacle.</p>",
    "4": "<p><b>Moses said to all the congregation of Israel, 'This is the thing that YHWH has commanded: Take from among you a contribution to YHWH. Whoever is of a generous heart, let him bring YHWH's contribution':</b> The Tabernacle is funded by a <em>terumah</em> (H8641, freewill offering/contribution) — a voluntary giving from a generous heart (<em>nadiv lev</em>, H5081+H3820, willing-hearted/generous). Unlike the census ransom (30:11-16, a fixed mandatory payment), the Tabernacle construction fund is entirely voluntary. The economic theology is intentional: God's house is built from glad generosity, not legal compulsion.</p>",
    "5": "<p><b>'Gold, silver, and bronze; blue and purple and scarlet yarns and fine twined linen, goats' hair':</b> The materials list repeats 25:3-7 verbatim — this is the execution announcement of the original divine instruction. The three metals (gold, silver, bronze) correspond to the Tabernacle's three zones of holiness. The four fabrics (blue, purple, scarlet, fine linen) are all luxury textiles; blue (<em>tekhelet</em>) and purple (<em>argaman</em>) were Phoenician dyes of exceptional cost, requiring thousands of murex shellfish per gram of dye. The voluntary bringing of these elite materials from Egypt's wealth (the spoils of the exodus) transforms the plunder of an empire into the furnishings of a sanctuary.</p>",
    "6": "<p><b>Tanned rams' skins, goatskins, acacia wood:</b> The leather coverings of the Tabernacle — tanned red-dyed rams' skins and <em>techashim</em> skins (sea cows? dugong? the exact animal is uncertain) — provided the outermost weather protection. Acacia wood (<em>shittim</em>) is the structural material for all the portable wooden elements: the boards, the pillars, the furniture frames. Its density and resistance to insect damage made it ideal for a portable sanctuary.</p>",
    "7": "<p><b>Oil for the light, spices for the anointing oil and for the fragrant incense:</b> The liturgical substances — oil for the lampstand (27:20), spices for the anointing oil (30:23-25) and incense (30:34-38) — are now included in the freewill offering call alongside the structural materials. The Tabernacle requires not only physical construction but ongoing liturgical supply; both are funded by communal generosity.</p>",
    "8": "<p><b>And onyx stones and stones for setting, for the ephod and for the breastpiece:</b> The precious stones for the high priest's garments — the two onyx shoulder stones engraved with tribal names (28:9-12) and the twelve breastpiece stones (28:15-21) — are the most personally directed of all the materials, belonging to the person of the high priest. Their inclusion in the freewill offering list means that Israel collectively clothes and equips their intercessor before God.</p>",
    "9": "<p><b>Let every skillful craftsman among you come and make all that YHWH has commanded: the tabernacle, its tent and its covering':</b> The call for skilled artisans (<em>chacham-lev</em>, wise/skilled-hearted) now goes to the entire community after the leaders' response (v27). The phrase <em>kol-chakham lev</em> (all who are skilled-hearted) is the same terminology as 31:6 for those whom God filled with skill alongside Bezalel and Oholiab. The community's skilled members are invited to participate in the construction — the Tabernacle is a communal craft project, not solely an elite commission.</p>",
    "10": "<p><b>Its frames, its bars, its pillars, and its bases</b>:</b> The structural elements of the Tabernacle frame — the <em>qerachim</em> (upright frames/planks), the <em>berichim</em> (crossbars), the <em>amudim</em> (pillars), and the <em>adanim</em> (silver socket-bases) — are the portable engineering system that allows a sanctuary of remarkable size (30 cubits by 10 cubits) to be assembled and disassembled in the wilderness. The silver bases (each weighing one talent = ~34 kg) were funded by the census ransom money (38:27), creating a literal base of redemption upon which the entire Tabernacle structure rested.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The ark and its poles, the mercy seat, and the veil of the screen — the inner core of the Most Holy Place, named first in the construction call to establish the hierarchy of holiness. The items are listed from inside outward (ark, screen/veil) and then the holy place items (table, lampstand, altar of incense) and finally the courtyard elements (altar of burnt offering, laver). The inward-to-outward organization mirrors the priest's movement from periphery to center in service.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The ark, its poles, the mercy seat, and the veil of the screen — these are the restricted elements, accessible only to the high priest on Yom Kippur. Their naming in the public construction call acknowledges that though the community builds them, they will never directly interact with them in service. The separation between construction and use is a distinctive feature of the Tabernacle's theology: all of Israel builds what only the high priest may enter.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The table, its poles and all its utensils, and the bread of the Presence — the <em>lechem panim</em> (bread of the Presence/face-bread) is the showbread displayed permanently before YHWH, replaced weekly by the priests. It is simultaneously a firstfruits offering and a covenant meal-symbol — twelve loaves for twelve tribes, the entire community present in bread before God.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The lampstand for the light, with its utensils and its lamps, and the oil for the light — the menorah and its maintenance supplies. The oil for light (<em>shemen lama'or</em>) is specified separately from the anointing oil, confirming that the lampstand oil was pure olive oil (27:20), not the five-spice compound of the anointing oil (30:23-25). The permanent lamp's burning through the night was the visible sign of divine attention — the eye of God never closed over his house.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The altar of incense and its poles, the anointing oil and the fragrant incense, and the screen for the door at the entrance of the tabernacle — the doorway screen (<em>masakh hapetach</em>) at the tent's entrance performed the same function for the outer door as the veil did for the inner: controlling access and maintaining the holiness gradient from courtyard to holy place.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The altar of burnt offering with its grating of bronze, its poles, and all its utensils, the basin and its stand — the courtyard altar and laver are listed last because they are the first things encountered when entering from outside. The bronze grating (<em>michbar nechoshet</em>) of the altar was the metal grid within the altar that held the sacrifices over the fire pit; its bronze material reflects its courtyard (outer zone) placement.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The hangings of the court, its pillars and its bases, and the screen for the gate of the court — the courtyard enclosure (100 by 50 cubits, 27:9-18) was the accessible space for ordinary Israelites; the hanging screen at the courtyard gate marked the first threshold between secular and sacred space. Every Israelite could enter the courtyard; only priests could advance beyond.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The pegs of the tabernacle and the pegs of the court, and their cords — the tent pegs (<em>yetedot</em>) and their ropes secured the Tabernacle structure against wind in the wilderness. The mundane hardware — pegs and cords — is included in the list of sacred construction elements, confirming that every component of the Tabernacle, however utilitarian, is consecrated to divine service.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The finely worked garments for ministering in the holy place, the holy garments for Aaron the priest, and the garments of his sons for their service as priests — the priestly vestments are listed last in the materials call because they are the most personal and status-defining of all the sacred objects. They are made by the skilled artisans (28:3) from the community's donated materials; in receiving and wearing them, Aaron and his sons embody the covenant community's entire approach to God.</p>",
    "20": "<p><b>Then all the congregation of Israel departed from the presence of Moses:</b> The assembly dissolves and the people return to their tents to gather their contributions. The absence of verbal response — no question asked, no objection raised — is notable; the community simply goes to act. This silent obedience contrasts with the volatile assembly of ch 32; the covenant renewal has produced a different kind of people, at least for this moment.</p>",
    "21": "<p><b>And they came, every one whose heart stirred him (<em>asher nesa'o libo</em>), and every one whose spirit moved him (<em>asher nadeva rucho</em>), and brought YHWH's contribution to be used for the tent of meeting':</b> Two phrases describe the freewill givers: <em>nesa'o libo</em> (whose heart was lifted/stirred) and <em>nadeva rucho</em> (whose spirit was willing/generous). The verb <em>nasa</em> (to lift) applied to the heart (<em>lev</em>) means a disposition elevated toward generosity; <em>nadav</em> (H5068, to be generous/willing) is the root of <em>nedavah</em> (freewill offering). Both phrases describe the motivated, uncoerced impulse to give — the divine Spirit working within the human spirit to produce generosity for the sanctuary.</p>",
    "22": "<p><b>So they came, both men and women. All who were of a willing heart brought brooches and earrings and signet rings and armlets, all sorts of gold objects, every man dedicating an offering of gold to YHWH:</b> The <em>jewelry</em> brought to the Tabernacle is the mirror image of the jewelry stripped and melted for the golden calf (32:2-4). The same community that funded the idol now redeems itself by funding the true divine dwelling. The inclusion of women as willing givers alongside men — named separately (<em>anashim al-nashim</em>) — acknowledges that women's wealth (their jewelry) constitutes a significant portion of the Tabernacle's gold supply.</p>",
    "23": "<p><b>And every one who possessed blue or purple or scarlet yarn or fine linen or goats' hair or tanned rams' skins or goatskins brought them:</b> The textile donations come from those who 'possessed' (<em>nimtza ito</em>, was found with him/her) the luxury materials — implying not everyone had them, but those who did brought all of them. The passive possession language (<em>nimtza</em>) may hint at providence: these luxury textiles were in Israel's hands because YHWH had given them favor before the Egyptians (12:36).</p>",
    "24": "<p><b>Everyone who could make a contribution of silver or bronze brought it as YHWH's contribution. And every one who possessed acacia wood of any use in the work brought it:</b> The bronze and silver contributions (along with acacia wood) complete the structural materials. <em>Kol asher herim terumas kesef unechoshet</em> (everyone who raised a contribution of silver or bronze) — the verb <em>herim</em> (to lift up) is also the root of <em>terumah</em> (contribution/wave offering), a term that literally means 'lifted/elevated thing.' The giving is enacted linguistically as the same gesture as the ritual elevation of an offering before YHWH.</p>",
    "25": "<p><b>And every skillful woman spun with her hands, and they all brought what they had spun in blue and purple and scarlet yarns and fine twined linen:</b> The women's spinning is explicitly identified as skilled craft — <em>kol ishah chakhemat-lev</em> (every woman wise-hearted), the same formula used for Bezalel's male artisan companions (31:6). The woman-spinners use the same <em>chochmah</em> (wisdom/skill) terminology as the Spirit-filled male craftsmen, and their contribution is structural: without the woven linen and yarns, the Tabernacle's curtains cannot be made. The female workforce of the Tabernacle is invisible in some readings but named and qualified here.</p>",
    "26": "<p><b>All the women whose hearts moved them with skill spun the goats' hair:</b> Goats' hair (<em>izim</em>) spinning is mentioned separately from the fine linen because it is a different technical process — coarser fiber, different twist — and produces the second layer of the Tabernacle's covering. The phrase <em>asher nasa liban otana bechokhmah</em> (whose heart lifted them in skill) is unique — the combination of <em>nasa</em> (lifted/stirred) with <em>chokhmah</em> (wisdom/skill) suggests that artistic skill itself is experienced as a heart-lifting gift, not merely a learned technique.</p>",
    "27": "<p><b>And the leaders (<em>nesi'im</em>) brought onyx stones and stones for setting, for the ephod and for the breastpiece:</b> The leaders (tribal chieftains) bring the most expensive individual items: the gem stones for the high priest's garments and the spices, oil, and lighting oil. The social stratification of giving is preserved — ordinary Israelites give what they have; leaders give what only they can afford. The <em>nesi'im</em> are the same tribal leaders who will lead the Num 1 census; their patronage of the priestly vestments ties tribal leadership to priestly mediation.</p>",
    "28": "<p><b>And spices and oil for the light, and for the anointing oil, and for the fragrant incense:</b> The liturgical substances — the most refined and costly of all the donations — are provided by the leaders. Spices for the anointing oil and incense were imported luxury goods; the fact that Israel possessed them reflects the Egyptian spoils of the exodus. The chain of provision is explicit: Egypt's gold and spices, given to Israel through divine favor, are now consecrated to YHWH's dwelling.</p>",
    "29": "<p><b>All the men and women, the people of Israel, whose heart moved them to bring anything for the work that YHWH had commanded by Moses to be done brought it as a freewill offering (<em>nedavah</em>) to YHWH:</b> The summary verse balances the individual categories with the comprehensive statement: men and women, all Israel, heart-moved, voluntarily. The word <em>nedavah</em> (freewill offering) is the theological signature of the entire construction fund — it is given not because it must be, but because the givers want to. The Tabernacle is thus a monument not only to divine design but to human generosity freely given in response to covenant grace.</p>",
    "30": "<p><b>Then Moses said to the people of Israel, 'See, YHWH has called by name Bezalel the son of Uri, son of Hur, of the tribe of Judah':</b> The re-announcement of Bezalel after the golden-calf interruption (he was first named in 31:2) signals continuity: the crisis of ch 32-34 has not canceled the construction project or the divine appointments. Moses uses the same formula as the first announcement — <em>qara beshem</em> (called by name) — confirming that the divine election is unchanged. The fact that Bezalel is from Judah while the crisis was caused by Levitical Aaron (32:1-6) has an implicit contrast: the royal tribe's artisan succeeds where the priestly tribe's leader failed.</p>",
    "31": "<p><b>'And he has filled him with the Spirit of God, with skill, with intelligence, with knowledge, and with all craftsmanship':</b> The re-statement of Bezalel's Spirit-endowment from 31:3 repeats the three-fold cognitive gift: <em>chokmah</em> (skill/wisdom), <em>tevunah</em> (intelligence/understanding), <em>da'at</em> (knowledge). The context of re-announcement after the golden-calf episode emphasizes that the Spirit's work in artisanal skill is the divine answer to the Spirit-less artisanship of Aaron's calf-making (32:4: <em>vayitsarehu bacharet</em>, he fashioned it with an engraving tool — without divine commissioning or Spirit-filling).</p>",
    "32": "<p><b>'To devise artistic designs, to work in gold and silver and bronze':</b> <em>Lachshov machashavot</em> (to devise artistic plans) — the intellectual-creative dimension of Bezalel's Spirit-given capacity. The divine Spirit enables not only execution but conception; Bezalel thinks artistically before he works artistically. The three metals — gold (inner sanctuary), silver (outer fittings), bronze (courtyard) — represent the entire material range of the Tabernacle, confirming Bezalel's comprehensive mandate.</p>",
    "33": "<p><b>'In cutting stones for setting, and in carving wood, to work in every skilled craft':</b> The comprehensive scope of Bezalel's craft — gem cutting, woodcarving, metalwork — is re-confirmed. The phrase <em>bechol melechet machashevet</em> (in every work of skilled craft/design) uses <em>melechet</em> (work/craft) with <em>machashevet</em> (design/thought), the same pairing as in 31:4. The Tabernacle requires both conceptual design and skilled execution; Bezalel carries both gifts.</p>",
    "34": "<p><b>'And he has inspired him to teach, both him and Oholiab the son of Ahisamach of the tribe of Dan':</b> The teaching gift is a specific addition to the earlier commissioning: <em>velehorot natan belibo</em> (and to teach, he has put in his heart). Bezalel and Oholiab are not only master craftsmen but master teachers — they can transmit their skill to others. This pedagogical gift is essential for a project that requires many workers; the Spirit's endowment for craft includes the ability to multiply that craft through instruction. The paired commissioning (Judah + Dan, south + north) maintains the representative-of-all-Israel character of the artisan leadership.</p>",
    "35": "<p><b>He has filled them with skill to do every sort of work done by an engraver or by a designer or by an embroiderer in blue and purple and scarlet yarns and fine twined linen, or by a weaver — by any sort of workman or skilled designer':</b> The comprehensive list of artistic specializations — engraving (<em>charash</em>), design/planning (<em>choshev</em>), embroidery (<em>roqem</em>), weaving (<em>orag</em>) — covers the full range of ancient textile and metalwork arts. The divine Spirit's scope of endowment matches the technical scope of the project: whatever the Tabernacle requires, the Spirit equips. The implicit theology is that there is no domain of human skilled work that lies outside the Spirit's capacity to inhabit and empower.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'exodus')
    merge_comm(existing, EXODUS_CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'exodus', existing)
    print('Exodus 33-35 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
